14 SUMMARY
1155 This bill repeals certain statutes related to correspondence schools and updates
1166 application requirements for degree-granting educational institutions. The bill requires a
1177 degree-granting educational institution to pay an application fee for the initial application
1188 that reflects the costs to the Department of Education for processing the application, as
1199 determined by the Commissioner of Education, and clarifies that temporary approval to use
2200 the name "community college," "college" or "university" may not be used as a basis for a
2211 recommendation by the State Board of Education for permanent degree-granting authority.
2222 The bill also allows the state board to recommend an educational institution to the
2233 Legislature for degree-granting authority without additional review if the state board has
2244 approved or renewed approval for the institution to offer academic programs in the State
2255 within 5 years of the institution’s application for degree-granting authority and the
2266 institution has applied for degree-granting authority only for degrees for which the
2277 institution offers academic programs approved by the state board. The bill requires the state
2288 board to provide any reports resulting from completed state board reviews of the applicant
2299 educational institution to the joint standing committee of the Legislature having jurisdiction
3300 over education matters upon recommending the institution for degree-granting authority.
